Share this on WhatsAppSpread the loveGov. Atiku Bagudu of Kebbi has signed the child rights protection bill into law.
Bagudu also signed a bill on Prohibiting Violence Against Individuals and the Law for the Protection of Child Rights (Child Right Protection Law).
Speaking after signing the Bills, the governor explained that the action would further demonstrate to the International Community the commitment of Kebbi to effectively apply the law against gender violence and strengthen the protection of children.
“These laws will also strengthen child protection, although some of our laws already provided for that.
“This is to strengthen them and draw attention to the need to do more,” he noted.
The governor thanked the Kebbi House of Assembly for its hard work and determination to pass the bills in conformity with the cultural and religious values of the people of the state.
He equally appreciated religious leaders and traditional rulers for reviewing the law to ensure conformity with religious stipulations.
Bagudu expressed appreciation to development partners and other groups for their support to the government which facilitated the actualization of the law and its application.
The governor expressed gratitude to his wife, Dr. Zainab Shinkafi-Bagudu for her immense support as well as for initiating and facilitating awareness and formulation of the law against gender violence and protection of children’s rights and privileges.
The governor expressed optimism that the law would be beneficial to the people of the state.
The News Agency of Nigeria reports that the Kebbi House of Assembly on Oct. 5, 2021, passed the bill for a law to provide and protect the Right of the Child in Kebbi State and other related matters.
NAN reports that Kebbi is the 30thstate in Nigeria to sign the child protection bill into law.
